<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="inference-for-regression" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Inference for Regression</title>

  <p>
    In this chapter, we revisit the regression model studied in <xref ref="regression"/> and
    <xref ref="multiple-regression"/>. We do it by taking into account the inferential statistics
    methods introduced in <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> and <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/>.
    We will show that when applying the linear regression methods introduced earlier on sample
    data, we can gain insight into the relationships between the response and explanatory
    variables of an entire population.
  </p>

  <!-- Needed packages -->
  <subsection xml:id="inf-packages">
    <title>Needed packages</title>
    <p>
      If needed, read <xref ref="sec-packages"/> for information on how to install and load
      R packages.
    </p>
    <program language="r">
      <input>
library(tidyverse)
library(moderndive)
library(infer)
library(gridExtra)
library(GGally)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Recall that loading the <c>tidyverse</c> package loads many packages that we have
      encountered earlier. For details refer to <xref ref="tidyverse-package"/>. The packages
      <c>moderndive</c> and <c>infer</c> contain functions and data frames that will be used
      in this chapter.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="simple-linear-regression-model">
    <title>The simple linear regression model</title>

    <subsection xml:id="un-member-states-revisited">
      <title>UN member states revisited</title>

      <p>
        We briefly review the example of UN member states covered in <xref ref="model1"/>.
        Data on the current UN member states, as of 2024, can be found in the
        <c>un_member_states_2024</c> data frame included in the <c>moderndive</c> package.
        As we did in <xref ref="model1"/>, we save these data as a new data frame called
        <c>UN_data_ch10</c>, <c>select()</c> the required variables, and include rows without
        missing data using <c>na.omit()</c>:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
UN_data_ch10 &lt;- un_member_states_2024 |>
  select(country,
         life_exp = life_expectancy_2022,
         fert_rate = fertility_rate_2022) |>
  na.omit()
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        The data frame contains a summary of two numerical variables. Using simple linear
        regression<idx><h>regression</h><h>simple linear</h></idx> between the response
        variable fertility rate (<c>fert_rate</c>) or <m>y</m>, and the regressor life
        expectancy (<c>life_exp</c>) or <m>x</m>, the regression line is:
      </p>
      <me>
        \widehat{y}_i = b_0 + b_1 \cdot x_i.
      </me>
      <p>
        We have presented this equation in <xref ref="model1"/>, but we now add the subscript
        <m>i</m> to represent the <m>i</m>th observation or country in the UN dataset, and we
        let <m>i = 1, \dots, n</m>. The value <m>x_i</m> represents the life expectancy value
        for the <m>i</m>th member state, and <m>\widehat{y}_i</m> is the fitted fertility rate
        for the <m>i</m>th member state. The fitted fertility rate is the result of the
        regression line and is typically different than the observed response <m>y_i</m>. The
        residual is given as the difference <m>y_i - \widehat{y}_i</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        As discussed in <xref ref="leastsquares"/>, the intercept (<m>b_0</m>) and slope
        (<m>b_1</m>) are the regression coefficients, such that the regression line is the
        <q>best-fitting</q> line based on the least-squares criterion. In other words, the
        fitted values <m>\widehat{y}</m> calculated using the least-squares coefficients
        (<m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>) minimize the <em>sum of the squared residuals</em>:
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \widehat{y}_i)^2.
      </me>
      <p>
        As we did in <xref ref="model1"/>, we fit the linear regression model by calculating
        the regression coefficients, <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>, that minimize the sum of
        squared residuals. To do this in R, we use the <c>lm()</c> function with the formula
        <c>fert_rate ~ life_exp</c> and save the solution in <c>simple_model</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
simple_model &lt;- lm(fert_rate ~ life_exp, data = UN_data_ch10)
coef(simple_model)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
(Intercept)    life_exp 
 12.6130315  -0.1374889
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The regression line is <m>\widehat{y}_i = b_0 + b_1 \cdot x_i</m>, where <m>x_i</m>
        is the life expectancy for the <m>i</m>th country and <m>\widehat{y}_i</m> is the
        corresponding fitted fertility rate. The <m>b_1</m> coefficient is the slope of the
        regression line; for any country, if the life expectancy were to increase by about one
        year, we would expect an associated reduction of the fertility rate by about 0.137
        units.
      </p>
      <p>
        We visualize the relationship by plotting the scatterplot of fertility rate against
        life expectancy for all the UN member states with complete data, and include the
        regression line (<xref ref="fig-regline-ch10"/>):
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
ggplot(UN_data_ch10, aes(x = life_exp, y = fert_rate)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Life Expectancy (x)",
       y = "Fertility Rate (y)",
       title = "Relationship between fertility rate and life expectancy") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, linewidth = 0.5)
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-regline-ch10">
        <caption>Relationship with regression line for UN member states data.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-regline-ch10.png" width="80%">
          <description>Scatterplot of fertility rate versus life expectancy for UN member states with a fitted linear regression line.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Finally, we review how to determine the fitted values and residuals. France is one
        of the UN member states. We can find its row number using <c>rowid_to_column()</c>
        and <c>filter()</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
UN_data_ch10 |>
  rowid_to_column() |>
  filter(country == "France") |>
  pull(rowid)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
[1] 57
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        We can determine France's fitted fertility rate from the regression line and compare
        it to the observed value. Using R we are not required to manually calculate the
        fitted values and residuals. We do this directly using <c>get_regression_points()</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
simple_model |>
  get_regression_points() |>
  filter(ID == 57)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 1 × 5
     ID fert_rate life_exp fert_rate_hat residual
  &lt;int&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;         &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1    57       1.8     82.6          1.26    0.542
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        We can retrieve this information for all observations:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
simple_model |>
  get_regression_points()
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 183 × 5
      ID fert_rate life_exp fert_rate_hat residual
   &lt;int&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;         &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
 1     1       4.3     53.6          5.24   -0.937
 2     2       1.4     79.5          1.69   -0.287
 3     3       2.7     78.0          1.88    0.815
 4     4       5       62.1          4.07    0.926
 5     5       1.6     77.8          1.92   -0.316
 6     6       1.9     78.3          1.85    0.054
 7     7       1.6     76.1          2.15   -0.546
 8     8       1.6     83.1          1.19    0.411
 9     9       1.5     82.3          1.30    0.198
10    10       1.6     74.2          2.42   -0.818
# ℹ 173 more rows
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        This concludes our review of material covered in <xref ref="model1"/>. We now explain
        how to use this information for statistical inference.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end UN member states revisited -->


    <subsection xml:id="simple-linear-model">
      <title>The model</title>

      <p>
        As we did in <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> on confidence intervals and
        <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/> on hypothesis testing, we present this problem in the
        context of a population and associated parameters of interest. We then collect a random
        sample from this population and use it to estimate these parameters.
      </p>
      <p>
        We assume that this population has a response variable (<m>Y</m>), an explanatory
        variable (<m>X</m>), and there is a <em>statistical linear relationship</em> between
        these variables, given by the linear model
      </p>
      <me>
        Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X + \epsilon,
      </me>
      <p>
        where <m>\beta_0</m> is the population intercept and <m>\beta_1</m> is the population
        slope. These are the parameters of the model that alongside the explanatory variable
        (<m>X</m>) produce the equation of a line. The statistical part of this relationship
        is given by <m>\epsilon</m>, a random variable called the <term>error term</term>.
        The error term accounts for the portion of <m>Y</m> that is not explained by the line.
      </p>
      <p>
        We make additional assumptions about the distribution of the error term, <m>\epsilon</m>.
        The assumed expected value of the error term is zero, and the assumed standard deviation
        is equal to a positive constant called <m>\sigma</m>:
        <m>E(\epsilon) = 0</m> and <m>SD(\epsilon) = \sigma.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        If you were to take a large number of observations from this population, we would
        expect the error terms sometimes to be greater than zero and sometimes less than zero,
        but on average, be equal to zero. Similarly, some error terms will be very close to
        zero and others very far from zero, but on average, we would expect them to be roughly
        <m>\sigma</m> units away from zero.
      </p>
      <p>
        Recall the square of the standard deviation is called the variance, so
        <m>Var(\epsilon) = \sigma^2</m>. The variance of the error term is equal to
        <m>\sigma^2</m> regardless of the value of <m>X</m>. This property is called
        <term>homoskedasticity</term><idx><h>homoskedasticity</h></idx> or constancy of
        the variance.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end The model -->


    <subsection xml:id="sample-regression-inference">
      <title>Using a sample for inference</title>

      <p>
        As we did in <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> and <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/>,
        we use a sample to estimate the parameters in the population. We use data collected
        from the Old Faithful Geyser in Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming, USA. This
        dataset contains the <c>duration</c> of the geyser eruption in seconds and the
        <c>waiting</c> time to the next eruption in minutes. These data are stored in the
        <c>old_faithful_2024</c> data frame in the <c>moderndive</c> package.
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
old_faithful_2024
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 114 × 6
   eruption_id date        time waiting webcam duration
         &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;date&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;
 1     1473854 2024-08-19   538     180 Yes         235
 2     1473352 2024-08-15  1541     184 Yes         259
 3     1473337 2024-08-15  1425     116 Yes         137
 4     1473334 2024-08-15  1237     188 Yes         222
 5     1473331 2024-08-15  1131     106 Yes         105
 6     1473328 2024-08-15   944     187 Yes         180
 7     1473207 2024-08-14  1231     182 Yes         244
 8     1473201 2024-08-14  1041     190 Yes         278
 9     1473137 2024-08-13  1810     138 Yes         249
10     1473108 2024-08-13  1624     186 Yes         262
# ℹ 104 more rows
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        By looking at the first row we can tell, for example, that an eruption on August 19,
        2024, at 5:38 AM lasted 235 seconds, and the waiting time for the next eruption was
        180 minutes. We next display the summary for these two variables:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
old_faithful_2024 |>
  select(duration, waiting) |>
  tidy_summary()
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 2 × 11
  column       n group type      min    Q1  mean median    Q3   max    sd
  &lt;chr&gt;    &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;chr&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;
1 duration   114 &lt;NA&gt;  numeric    99  180   217.   240.  259    300  59.0
2 waiting    114 &lt;NA&gt;  numeric   102  139.  160.   176.  184.   201  29.9
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        We have a sample of eruptions, lasting between 99 seconds and 300 seconds, and the
        waiting time to the next eruption was between 102 minutes and 201 minutes. Observe
        that each observation is a pair of values, the value of the explanatory variable
        (<m>X</m>) and the value of the response (<m>Y</m>). The sample takes the form:
      </p>
      <me>
        (x_1, y_1),\quad (x_2, y_2),\quad \dots,\quad (x_n, y_n),
      </me>
      <p>
        where <m>(x_i, y_i)</m> is the pair of explanatory and response values for the
        <m>i</m>th observation. <xref ref="fig-geyserplot1"/> shows the scatterplot for the
        entire sample with some transparency set to check for overplotting:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
ggplot(old_faithful_2024, aes(x = duration, y = waiting)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  labs(x = "duration", y = "waiting")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-geyserplot1">
        <caption>Scatterplot of eruption duration and waiting time for Old Faithful geyser (2024).</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-geyserplot1.png" width="80%">
          <description>Scatterplot of waiting time (y-axis) versus eruption duration in seconds (x-axis) for Old Faithful geyser data. The relationship appears positive and approximately linear.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>The relationship seems positive and, to some extent, linear.</p>
    </subsection><!-- end Using a sample for inference -->


    <subsection xml:id="least-squares">
      <title>The method of least squares</title>

      <p>
        If the association of these variables is linear or approximately linear, we can apply
        the linear model described in <xref ref="simple-linear-model"/> to each observation in the sample:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>y_1 &amp;= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_1 + \epsilon_1</mrow>
        <mrow>y_2 &amp;= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_2 + \epsilon_2</mrow>
        <mrow>\vdots &amp;\phantom{= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x + \epsilon}\vdots</mrow>
        <mrow>y_n &amp;= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_n + \epsilon_n.</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        We want to use this model to describe the relationship between the explanatory variable
        and the response, but the parameters <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m> are unknown to
        us. We estimate these parameters using the random sample by applying the
        <em>least-squares</em> method introduced in <xref ref="model1"/>. We compute the
        estimators for the intercept (<m>\beta_0</m>) and slope (<m>\beta_1</m>) that minimize
        the <em>sum of squared residuals</em>:
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{i=1}^n \left[y_i - (\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_i)\right]^2.
      </me>
      <p>
        The solutions are the regression coefficients introduced in <xref ref="model1"/>:
        <m>b_0</m> is the estimator of <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>b_1</m> is the estimator of
        <m>\beta_1</m>. They are called the <term>least squares estimators</term>
        <idx><h>least squares estimators</h></idx> and their mathematical expressions are:
      </p>
      <me>
        b_1 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)(y_i - \bar y)}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}
        \quad\text{ and }\quad b_0 = \bar y - b_1 \cdot \bar x.
      </me>
      <p>
        Furthermore, an <em>estimator</em> for the standard deviation of <m>\epsilon_i</m> is
        given by:
      </p>
      <me>
        s = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \left[y_i - (b_0 + b_1 \cdot x_i)\right]^2}{n-2}}
        = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \left(y_i - \widehat{y}_i\right)^2}{n-2}}.
      </me>
      <p>
        These or equivalent calculations are done in R when using the <c>lm()</c> function.
        For <c>old_faithful_2024</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
# Fit regression model:
model_1 &lt;- lm(waiting ~ duration, data = old_faithful_2024)

# Get the coefficients and standard deviation for the model
coef(model_1)
sigma(model_1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
[1] 20.3701
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        Based on these data and assuming the linear model is appropriate, we can say that for
        every additional second that an eruption lasts, the waiting time to the next eruption
        increases, on average, by 0.37 minutes. Any eruption lasts longer than zero seconds,
        so the intercept has no meaningful interpretation in this example. Finally, we roughly
        expect the waiting time for the next eruption to be 20.37 minutes away from the
        regression line value, on average.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end The method of least squares -->


    <subsection xml:id="properties-least-squares">
      <title>Properties of the least squares estimators</title>

      <p>
        The least squares method produces the <em>best-fitting</em> line by selecting the
        least squares estimators, <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>, that make the sum of residual
        squares the smallest possible. But the choice of <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m> depends
        on the sample observed. For every random sample taken from the data, different values
        for <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m> will be determined. In that sense, the least squares
        estimators, <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>, are random variables and as such, they have
        very useful properties:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m> are <em>unbiased estimators</em> of <m>\beta_0</m>
            and <m>\beta_1</m>: <m>E(b_0) = \beta_0</m> and <m>E(b_1) = \beta_1</m>. This
            means that, for some random samples, <m>b_1</m> will be greater than <m>\beta_1</m>
            and for others less than <m>\beta_1</m>. On average, <m>b_1</m> will be equal to
            <m>\beta_1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m> are linear combinations of the observed responses
            <m>y_1, y_2, \dots, y_n</m>. This means that, for example for <m>b_1</m>, there
            are known constants <m>c_1, c_2, \dots, c_n</m> such that
            <m>b_1 = \sum_{i=1}^n c_iy_i</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>s^2</m> is an unbiased estimator of the variance <m>\sigma^2</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        These properties will be useful in the next section, once we perform theory-based
        inference for regression.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end Properties of the least squares estimators -->


    <subsection xml:id="relating-regression-to-other-methods">
      <title>Relating basic regression to other methods</title>

      <p>
        To wrap up this section, we investigate how regression relates to two different
        statistical techniques: the difference in sample means (covered already in this book)
        and ANOVA (new to the text but related). We see how both can be represented in the
        regression framework.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="two-sample-diff-means-reg">
        <title>Two-sample difference in means</title>
        <p>
          The two-sample difference in means is a common statistical technique used to compare
          the means of two groups, as seen in <xref ref="ht-case-study"/>. It can be
          represented in the regression framework by using a dummy variable to represent the
          two groups. Let's consider the <c>movies_sample</c> data frame in the
          <c>moderndive</c> package. We compare the average rating for the genres
          <q>Action</q> versus <q>Romance</q> using <c>lm()</c> with a dummy variable for
          the genre:
        </p>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
mod_diff_means &lt;- lm(rating ~ genre, data = movies_sample)
get_regression_table(mod_diff_means)
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
# A tibble: 2 × 7
  term          estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;            &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept         5.28     0.265     19.9    0        4.75      5.80
2 genre-Romance     1.05     0.364      2.88   0.005    0.321     1.77
          </output>
        </console>
        <p>
          The <c>p_value</c> for the <c>genre: Romance</c> row is the <m>p</m>-value for the
          hypothesis test:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>H_0&amp;: \text{action and romance have the same mean rating}</mrow>
          <mrow>H_A&amp;: \text{action and romance have different mean ratings.}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          This <m>p</m>-value result matches closely with what was found in
          <xref ref="ht-case-study"/>, but here we are using a theory-based approach with a
          linear model. The <c>estimate</c> for the <c>genre: Romance</c> row is the observed
          difference in means between the <q>Action</q> and <q>Romance</q> genres (with the
          sign switched since <q>Action</q> is the reference level).
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="anova-in-regression">
        <title>ANOVA</title>
        <p>
          ANOVA, or analysis of variance, is a statistical technique used to compare the means
          of three or more groups. ANOVA can be represented in the regression framework by
          using dummy variables to represent the groups. We compare the <c>popularity</c> values
          in the <c>spotify_by_genre</c> data frame from the <c>moderndive</c> package across
          the genres <c>country</c>, <c>hip-hop</c>, and <c>rock</c> (see <xref ref="fig-pop-by-genre-plot"/>):
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
spotify_for_anova &lt;- spotify_by_genre |>
  select(artists, track_name, popularity, track_genre) |>
  filter(track_genre %in% c("country", "hip-hop", "rock"))
          </input>
        </program>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
spotify_for_anova |>
  slice_sample(n = 5)
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
# A tibble: 5 × 4
  artists           track_name                            popularity track_genre
  &lt;chr&gt;             &lt;chr&gt;                                      &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;      
1 Mustafa Zahid     Toh Phir Aao                                  60 hip-hop    
2 Steve Miller Band Abracadabra                                    0 country    
3 Michael Ray       Time Marches On (The Bootlegger Sess…          0 country    
4 Vilen             Aankhein                                      63 hip-hop    
5 Alan Jackson      Good Time                                     71 country
          </output>
        </console>

        <figure xml:id="fig-pop-by-genre-plot">
          <caption>Boxplot of popularity by genre.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-pop-by-genre-plot.png" width="75%">
            <description>Side-by-side boxplots of track popularity for country, hip-hop, and rock genres from the Spotify dataset.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(spotify_for_anova, aes(x = track_genre, y = popularity)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Genre", y = "Popularity")
          </input>
        </program>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
mean_popularities_by_genre &lt;- spotify_for_anova |>
  group_by(track_genre) |>
  summarize(mean_popularity = mean(popularity))
mean_popularities_by_genre
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
# A tibble: 3 × 2
  track_genre mean_popularity
  &lt;chr&gt;                 &lt;dbl&gt;
1 country                17.0
2 hip-hop                37.8
3 rock                   19.0
          </output>
        </console>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
mod_anova &lt;- lm(popularity ~ track_genre, data = spotify_for_anova)
get_regression_table(mod_anova)
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
# A tibble: 3 × 7
  term                estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;                  &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept              17.0      0.976     17.4    0       15.1      18.9 
2 track_genre-hip-hop    20.7      1.38      15.0    0       18.0      23.4 
3 track_genre-rock        1.97     1.38       1.43   0.153   -0.733     4.68
          </output>
        </console>
        <p>
          The <c>estimate</c> for the <c>track_genre: hip-hop</c> and <c>track_genre: rock</c>
          rows are the differences in means compared to the <q>country</q> genre (the reference
          level). The <c>p_value</c> column shows that <c>hip-hop</c> has a statistically
          higher mean popularity compared to <c>country</c>, while <c>rock</c> does not have a
          statistically significant difference at the 5% level.
        </p>
        <p>
          The traditional ANOVA doesn't give this level of granularity. It can be performed
          using the <c>aov()</c> function:
        </p>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
aov(popularity ~ track_genre, data = spotify_for_anova) |>
  anova()
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
Analysis of Variance Table

Response: popularity
              Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(&gt;F)    
track_genre    2  261843  130922  137.43 &lt; 2.2e-16 ***
Residuals   2997 2855039     953                      
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1
          </output>
        </console>
        <p>
          The small <m>p</m>-value leads us to reject the null hypothesis that the mean
          popularities are equal across the three genres, consistent with the linear model
          results. However, ANOVA only tells us that a difference exists; the linear model
          reveals which specific means differ.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-1">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What does the error term <m>\epsilon</m> in the linear model
              <m>Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X + \epsilon</m> represent?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The exact value of the response variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>The predicted value of the response variable based on the model.</p></li>
              <li><p>The part of the response variable not explained by the line.</p></li>
              <li><p>The slope of the linear relationship between <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. The error term represents the part of the response variable not explained by the linear relationship.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-2">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Which of the following is a property of the least squares estimators
              <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>They are biased estimators of the population parameters <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>They are linear combinations of the observed responses <m>y_1, y_2, \ldots, y_n</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>They are always equal to the population parameters <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>They depend on the specific values of the explanatory variable <m>X</m> only.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. The least squares estimators are linear combinations of the observed responses.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-3">
          <statement>
            <p>
              How can the difference in means between two groups be represented in a linear
              regression model?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>By adding an interaction term between the groups and the response variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>By fitting separate regression lines for each group and comparing their slopes.</p></li>
              <li><p>By including a dummy variable to represent the groups.</p></li>
              <li><p>By subtracting the mean of one group from the mean of the other and using this difference as the predictor.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. Including a dummy variable to represent the two groups allows the difference in means to be captured by the regression slope.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Relating basic regression to other methods -->

  </section><!-- end The simple linear regression model -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="theory-simple-regression">
    <title>Theory-based inference for simple linear regression</title>

    <p>
      This section introduces the conceptual framework (see <xref ref="framework-simple-lm"/> and <xref ref="se-simple-lm"/>) needed for theory-based inference for
      regression and discusses the two most prominent methods for inference: confidence
      intervals (<xref ref="conf-intervals-b0-b1"/>) and hypothesis tests (<xref ref="hypo-test-simple-lm"/>). Some of this material is slightly more technical than
      other sections in this chapter, but most of the material is illustrated by working with
      a real example and interpretations and explanations complement the theory.
      <xref ref="regression-table"/> presents the R code needed to calculate relevant
      quantities for inference.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="framework-simple-lm">
      <title>Conceptual framework</title>

      <p>
        We start by reviewing the assumptions of the linear model. We continue using
        <c>old_faithful_2024</c> to illustrate some of this framework. Since we assume a
        linear relationship between the <c>duration</c> of an eruption and the <c>waiting</c>
        time to the next eruption, we can express the linear relationship for the <m>i</m>th
        observation as <m>y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_i + \epsilon_i</m> for
        <m>i=1,\dots,n</m>. The error term <m>\epsilon_i</m> is a random variable that
        represents how different the observed response <m>y_i</m> is from the expected
        response <m>\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_i</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We can illustrate the role of the error term using two observations from
        <c>old_faithful_2024</c>. We select the 49th and 51st observations using
        <c>slice()</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
old_faithful_2024 |>
  slice(c(49, 51))
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 2 × 6
  eruption_id date        time waiting webcam duration
        &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;date&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;
1     1469584 2024-07-18  1117     139 Yes         236
2     1469437 2024-07-17  1157     176 Yes         236
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        Observe that the <c>duration</c> time is the same for both observations, but the
        response <c>waiting</c> time is different. Assuming that the linear model is
        appropriate, both responses can be expressed as:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>y_{49} &amp;= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot 236 + \epsilon_{49}</mrow>
        <mrow>y_{51} &amp;= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot 236 + \epsilon_{51},</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        but <m>y_{49} = 139</m> and <m>y_{51} = 176</m>. The difference in responses is due
        to the error term as it accounts for variation in the response not accounted for by
        the linear model.
      </p>
      <p>
        In order to perform theory-based inference we require one additional assumption. We
        let the error term be normally distributed with an expected value (mean) equal to zero
        and a standard deviation equal to <m>\sigma</m>:
      </p>
      <me>
        \epsilon_i \sim \text{Normal}(0, \sigma).
      </me>
      <p>
        The response <m>y_i</m> (the <c>waiting</c> time for the <m>i</m>th eruption) is
        the sum of the constant <m>\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_i</m> and the normally
        distributed random variable <m>\epsilon_i</m>. Based on properties of random
        variables and the normal distribution, we can state that <m>y_i</m> is also a
        normally distributed random variable:
      </p>
      <me>
        y_i \sim \text{Normal}(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i\,,\, \sigma)
      </me>
      <p>
        for <m>i=1,\dots,n</m>. Since <m>\epsilon_i</m> and <m>\epsilon_j</m> are
        independent, <m>y_i</m> and <m>y_j</m> are also independent for any <m>i \ne j</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In addition, as stated in <xref ref="properties-least-squares"/>, the least-squares
        estimator <m>b_1</m> is a linear combination of the random variables
        <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m>. So <m>b_1</m> is also a random variable! The coefficient
        for the slope results from <em>a particular sample</em> of <m>n</m> pairs of
        <c>duration</c> and <c>waiting</c> times. If we collected a different sample of
        <m>n</m> pairs, the coefficient for the slope would likely be different due to
        <em>sampling variation</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m> are normally distributed and <m>b_1</m> is a linear
        combination of these random variables, <m>b_1</m> is also normally distributed:
      </p>
      <me>
        b_1 \sim \text{Normal} \left(\beta_1\,,\, \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}\right).
      </me>
      <p>
        Similarly, <m>b_0</m> is a linear combination of <m>y_1, \dots, y_n</m>:
      </p>
      <me>
        b_0 \sim \text{Normal} \left(\beta_0\,,\, \sigma\sqrt{\frac{1}{n} + \frac{\bar x^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}\right).
      </me>
      <p>
        We can also standardize the least-square estimators such that
      </p>
      <me>
        z_0 = \frac{b_0 - \beta_0}{\sigma\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{n} + \dfrac{\bar x^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}}
        \qquad\text{ and }\qquad
        z_1 = \frac{b_1 - \beta_1}{\dfrac{\sigma}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}}
      </me>
      <p>
        are the corresponding standard normal distributions.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end Conceptual framework -->


    <subsection xml:id="se-simple-lm">
      <title>Standard errors for least-squares estimators</title>

      <p>
        Recall that in <xref ref="sampling"/> and <xref ref="CLT-mean"/> we discussed that,
        due to the Central Limit Theorem, the distribution of the sample mean
        <m>\overline{X}</m> was approximately normal with mean equal to the parameter
        <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation equal to <m>\sigma/\sqrt{n}</m>. We then used the
        estimated standard error of <m>\overline{X}</m> to construct confidence intervals and
        hypothesis tests.
      </p>
      <p>
        An analogous treatment is now used to construct confidence intervals and hypothesis
        tests for <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>. The standard deviations for <m>b_0</m> and
        <m>b_1</m> are constructed using the sample size <m>n</m>, the values of the
        explanatory variables, their means, and the standard deviation of <m>y_i</m>
        (<m>\sigma</m>). While most of these values are known to us, <m>\sigma</m> is
        typically not.
      </p>
      <p>
        Instead, we estimate <m>\sigma</m> using the estimator of the standard deviation,
        <m>s</m>, introduced in <xref ref="least-squares"/>. The estimated standard deviation
        of <m>b_1</m> is called the <term>standard error</term>
        <idx><h>standard error</h><h>regression slope</h></idx> of <m>b_1</m>, and it is
        given by:
      </p>
      <me>
        SE(b_1) = \frac{s}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}.
      </me>
      <p>
        The <em>standard error</em> of <m>b_1</m> quantifies how much variation the estimator
        of the slope <m>b_1</m> may have for different random samples. The larger the standard
        error, the more variation we would expect in the estimated slope <m>b_1</m>. Similarly,
        the <em>standard error</em> of <m>b_0</m> is:
      </p>
      <me>
        SE(b_0) = s\sqrt{\frac{1}{n} + \frac{\bar x^2}{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}.
      </me>
      <p>
        When using the estimator <m>s</m> instead of the parameter <m>\sigma</m>, we are
        introducing additional uncertainty in our calculations. For example, we can
        standardize <m>b_1</m> using
      </p>
      <me>
        t = \frac{b_1 - \beta_1}{SE(b_1)}.
      </me>
      <p>
        Because we are using <m>s</m> to calculate <m>SE(b_1)</m>, the value of the standard
        error changes from sample to sample, and this additional uncertainty makes the
        distribution of the test statistic <m>t</m> no longer normal. Instead, it follows a
        <m>t</m>-distribution with <m>n-2</m> degrees of freedom. The loss of two degrees of
        freedom relates to the fact that we are estimating two parameters in the linear
        model: <m>\beta_0</m> and <m>\beta_1</m>.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end Standard errors -->


    <subsection xml:id="conf-intervals-b0-b1">
      <title>Confidence intervals for the least-squares estimators</title>

      <p>
        A 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> can be thought of as a range of
        plausible values for the population slope <m>\beta_1</m> of the linear relationship
        between <c>duration</c> and <c>waiting</c> times. In general, if the sampling
        distribution of an estimator is normal or approximately normal, the confidence
        interval for the relevant parameter is:
      </p>
      <me>
        \text{point estimate} \pm \text{margin of error}
        = \text{point estimate} \pm (\text{critical value} \cdot \text{standard error}).
      </me>
      <p>
        The formula for a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> is given by
        <m>b_1 \pm q \cdot SE(b_1)</m> where the critical value <m>q</m> is determined by
        the level of confidence required, the sample size used, and the corresponding degrees
        of freedom for the <m>t</m>-distribution. For the Old Faithful example, with
        <m>n - 2 = 112</m> degrees of freedom, the critical value is <m>q = 1.981</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The standard error for <m>b_1</m> using the formula presented earlier is:
      </p>
      <me>
        SE(b_1) = \frac{s}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \bar x)^2}}.
      </me>
      <p>
        We are 95% confident that the population slope <m>\beta_1</m> falls in this
        interval. The construction of a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_0</m> follows
        exactly the same steps using <m>b_0</m>, <m>SE(b_0)</m>, and the same critical
        value <m>q</m> as the degrees of freedom for the <m>t</m>-distribution are the same,
        <m>n-2</m>. The results of the confidence intervals are valid only if the linear
        model assumptions are satisfied, as discussed in <xref ref="model-fit"/>.
      </p>
    </subsection><!-- end Confidence intervals -->


    <subsection xml:id="hypo-test-simple-lm">
      <title>Hypothesis test for population slope</title>

      <p>
        To perform a hypothesis test for <m>\beta_1</m>, the general formulation of a
        two-sided test is:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>H_0&amp;: \beta_1 = B</mrow>
        <mrow>H_A&amp;: \beta_1 \ne B,</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        where <m>B</m> is the hypothesized value for <m>\beta_1</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <em>Test statistic.</em> The <m>t</m>-test statistic is given by
      </p>
      <me>
        t = \frac{b_1 - B}{SE(b_1)}.
      </me>
      <p>
        This test statistic follows, under the null hypothesis, a <m>t</m>-distribution with
        <m>n-2</m> degrees of freedom. A particularly useful test is whether there is a linear
        association between the explanatory variable and the response:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>H_0&amp;: \beta_1 = 0</mrow>
        <mrow>H_A&amp;: \beta_1 \ne 0.</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        For the Old Faithful example, the <em>null hypothesis</em> <m>H_0</m> assumes that the
        population slope <m>\beta_1</m> is 0, meaning there is <em>no linear relationship</em>
        between <c>duration</c> and <c>waiting</c> times. The test statistic is:
      </p>
      <me>
        t = \frac{b_1 - 0}{SE(b_1)}.
      </me>

      <p>
        <em>The <m>p</m>-value.</em> Recall the definition of the <m>p</m>-value: the
        probability of obtaining a test statistic just as extreme as or more extreme than the
        one observed, <em>assuming the null hypothesis</em> <m>H_0</m> is true. For a
        two-sided test, if the test statistic is <m>t = 2</m> for example, the <m>p</m>-value
        is the area under the <m>t</m>-curve to the left of <m>-2</m> and to the right of
        <m>2</m>, as shown in <xref ref="fig-pvalue1"/>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-pvalue1">
        <caption>Illustration of a two-sided <m>p</m>-value for a <m>t</m>-test.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-pvalue1.png" width="70%">
          <description>A t-distribution curve with the two shaded tail areas (to the left of -2 and to the right of 2) highlighted in blue, illustrating the two-sided p-value calculation.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        In the Old Faithful geyser eruptions example, the <m>p</m>-value was so small that R
        simply shows that it is equal to zero.
      </p>

      <p>
        <em>Interpretation.</em> Since the <m>p</m>-value was practically 0, for any choice
        of significance level <m>\alpha</m>, we would reject <m>H_0</m> in favor of
        <m>H_A</m>. We reject the null hypothesis that there is no linear relationship between
        <c>duration</c> and <c>waiting</c> times. We have enough statistical evidence to
        conclude that there is a linear relationship between these variables.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-4">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In the context of a linear regression model, what does the null hypothesis
              <m>H_0: \beta_1 = 0</m> represent?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>There is no linear association between the response and the explanatory variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>The difference between the observed and predicted values is zero.</p></li>
              <li><p>The linear association between response and explanatory variable crosses the origin.</p></li>
              <li><p>The probability of committing a Type II Error is zero.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>A. The null hypothesis <m>H_0: \beta_1 = 0</m> states that there is no linear association between the response and the explanatory variable.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-5">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Which of the following is an assumption of the linear regression model?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The error terms <m>\epsilon_i</m> are normally distributed with constant variance.</p></li>
              <li><p>The error terms <m>\epsilon_i</m> have a non-zero mean.</p></li>
              <li><p>The error terms <m>\epsilon_i</m> are dependent on each other.</p></li>
              <li><p>The explanatory variable must be normally distributed.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>A. The error terms are assumed to be normally distributed with constant variance (homoskedasticity) and mean zero.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-6">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What does it mean when we say that the slope estimator <m>b_1</m> is a random
              variable?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p><m>b_1</m> will be the same for every sample taken from the population.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>b_1</m> is a fixed value that does not change with different samples.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>b_1</m> can vary from sample to sample due to sampling variation.</p></li>
              <li><p><m>b_1</m> is always equal to the population slope <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. <m>b_1</m> is computed from a particular random sample; different samples yield different values of <m>b_1</m>, so it is a random variable.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Hypothesis test for population slope -->


    <subsection xml:id="regression-table">
      <title>The regression table in R</title>

      <p>
        The least-square estimates, standard errors, test statistics, <m>p</m>-values, and
        confidence interval bounds discussed in <xref ref="theory-simple-regression"/>, <xref ref="framework-simple-lm"/>, <xref ref="se-simple-lm"/>, <xref ref="conf-intervals-b0-b1"/>, and <xref ref="hypo-test-simple-lm"/> can be
        calculated all at once using the R wrapper function
        <c>get_regression_table()</c>
        <idx><h>get_regression_table()</h></idx> from the <c>moderndive</c> package. For
        <c>model_1</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
get_regression_table(model_1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 2 × 7
  term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;        &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept   79.5       7.31       10.9       0   65.0     93.9  
2 duration     0.371     0.032      11.4       0    0.307    0.435
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The first row in the regression table addresses inferences for the intercept
        <m>\beta_0</m>, and the second row deals with inference for the slope <m>\beta_1</m>.
        The columns present the following:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>The <c>estimate</c> column contains the least-squares estimates, <m>b_0</m> (first row) and <m>b_1</m> (second row).</p></li>
        <li><p>The <c>std_error</c> contains <m>SE(b_0)</m> and <m>SE(b_1)</m>, the standard errors for <m>b_0</m> and <m>b_1</m>, respectively.</p></li>
        <li><p>The <c>statistic</c> column contains the <m>t</m>-test statistic for <m>b_0</m> (first row) and <m>b_1</m> (second row), constructed using <m>t = b_1 / SE(b_1)</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The <c>p_value</c> is the probability of obtaining a test statistic just as extreme as or more extreme than the one observed, assuming the null hypothesis is true.</p></li>
        <li><p>The values <c>lower_ci</c> and <c>upper_ci</c> are the lower and upper bounds of a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m>.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </subsection><!-- end The regression table in R -->


    <subsection xml:id="model-fit">
      <title>Model fit and model assumptions</title>

      <p>
        We have introduced the linear model alongside assumptions about many of its elements
        and assumed all along that this is an appropriate representation of the relationship
        between the response and the explanatory variable. In real-life applications, it is
        uncertain whether the relationship is appropriately described by the linear model or
        whether all the assumptions we have introduced are satisfied.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not expect the linear model, or any other model, to be a perfect representation
        of a phenomenon presented in nature. Models are simplifications of reality in that
        they do not intend to represent exactly the relationship in question but rather provide
        useful approximations. This approach is known as the <term>principle of parsimony</term>
        or <term>Occam's razor</term>.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are four elements in the linear model we want to check. To help you remember
        them, we use the following acrostic:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em><alert>L</alert>inearity of relationship between variables</em> — Is the
            relationship between <m>y_i</m> and <m>x_i</m> truly linear for each
            <m>i = 1, \dots, n</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em><alert>I</alert>ndependence of each of the response values <m>y_i</m></em> —
            Are <m>y_i</m> and <m>y_j</m> independent for any <m>i \ne j</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em><alert>N</alert>ormality of the error terms</em> — Is the distribution of
            the error terms at least approximately normal?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em><alert>E</alert>quality or constancy of the variance for <m>y_i</m></em> —
            Is the variance of the response <m>y_i</m> always the same, regardless of the
            fitted value or regressor value?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        This acrostic follows the word <term>LINE</term>
        <idx><h>regression</h><h>model fit (LINE)</h></idx>. To check for <em>L</em>inearity,
        <em>N</em>ormality, and <em>E</em>qual or constant variance, we use the residuals of
        the linear regression via <em>residual diagnostics</em>
        <idx><h>residual analysis</h></idx>. To check for <em>I</em>ndependence, we can use
        the residuals if the data was collected in a time sequence, or otherwise independence
        may be achieved by taking a random sample.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="residuals-ch10">
        <title>Residuals</title>
        <p>
          Recall that given a random sample of <m>n</m> pairs <m>(x_1, y_1), \dots, (x_n, y_n)</m>
          the linear regression was given by <m>\widehat{y}_i = b_0 + b_1 \cdot x_i</m>.
          The residual is the <em>observed response</em> minus the <em>fitted value</em>:
        </p>
        <me>
          e_i = y_i - \widehat{y}_i \quad\text{ for } i = 1, \dots, n.
        </me>
        <p>
          Combining these two formulas we get
          <m>y_i = \underbrace{b_0 + b_1 \cdot x_i}_{\widehat{y}_i} + e_i</m>,
          which looks very similar to our linear model
          <m>y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_i + \epsilon_i</m>.
          In this context, residuals can be thought of as rough estimates of the error terms.
        </p>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="fig-residual-example"/>, we illustrate one particular residual for the
          Old Faithful geyser eruption. An arrow connects the observed waiting time (a circle)
          with the fitted waiting time (a square). The vertical distance between these two
          points is the value of the residual for this observation.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-residual-example">
          <caption>Example of observed value, fitted value, and residual for the Old Faithful data.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-residual-example.png" width="80%">
            <description>Scatterplot of Old Faithful duration versus waiting with the regression line. A single observation is highlighted with a circle for the observed value and a square for the fitted value, connected by an arrow indicating the residual.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          We can calculate all residuals by applying the <c>get_regression_points()</c>
          function to the regression model <c>model_1</c>:
        </p>
                <program language="r">
          <input>
# Fit regression model:
model_1 &lt;- lm(waiting ~ duration, data = old_faithful_2024)
# Get regression points:
fitted_and_residuals &lt;- get_regression_points(model_1)
fitted_and_residuals
          </input>
        </program>

        <console prompt="> ">
          <output>
# A tibble: 114 × 5
      ID waiting duration waiting_hat residual
   &lt;int&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;       &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
 1     1     180      235        167.    13.3 
 2     2     184      259        176.     8.43
 3     3     116      137        130.   -14.3 
 4     4     188      222        162.    26.2 
 5     5     106      105        118.   -12.4 
 6     6     187      180        146.    40.7 
 7     7     182      244        170.    12.0 
 8     8     190      278        183.     7.38
 9     9     138      249        172.   -33.9 
10    10     186      262        177.     9.31
# ℹ 104 more rows
          </output>
        </console>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="residual-diagnostics">
        <title>Residual diagnostics</title>
        <p>
          <em>Residual diagnostics</em> are used to verify conditions <em>L</em>, <em>N</em>,
          and <em>E</em>. One of the most useful plots is a <em>residual plot</em>, which is
          a scatterplot of the residuals against the fitted values. We use
          <c>fitted_and_residuals</c> to draw the scatterplot with the fitted values
          (<c>waiting_hat</c>) on the x-axis and the residuals (<c>residual</c>) on the
          y-axis, and add a horizontal line at 0:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(fitted_and_residuals, aes(x = waiting_hat, y = residual)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "duration", y = "residual") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "blue")
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="fig-scatt-and-residual"/> we show this residual plot (right) alongside
          the scatterplot for <c>duration</c> vs <c>waiting</c> (left). Note how the residuals
          on the left plot are determined by the vertical distance between the observed response
          and the linear regression. On the right plot, the effect of the linear regression has
          been removed.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-scatt-and-residual">
          <caption>The scatterplot (left) and residual plot (right) for the Old Faithful data.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-scatt-and-residual.png" width="90%">
            <description>Two side-by-side plots. Left: scatterplot of duration versus waiting with regression line. Right: scatterplot of fitted values versus residuals with a horizontal line at zero.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <em>Linearity of relationship.</em> We want to check whether the association between
          the response <m>y_i</m> and the explanatory variable <m>x_i</m> is <em>L</em>inear.
          A scatterplot of residuals against fitted values showing no patterns but simply a
          cloud of points that seems randomly assigned — called a <em>null plot</em> — does
          not show any evidence against the linearity assumption. This is largely the case for
          the Old Faithful geyser example.
        </p>
        <p>
          By contrast, <xref ref="fig-non-linear"/> shows a simulated example where the
          residual plot has a U-shaped polynomial curve. If this was the real data observed,
          using the linear regression would produce results that are not valid.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-non-linear">
          <caption>Example of a non-linear relationship (simulated data).</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-non-linear.png" width="90%">
            <description>Two side-by-side plots showing a simulated non-linear relationship. Left: scatterplot with regression line. Right: residual plot showing a clear U-shaped curve indicating the linearity assumption is violated.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <em>Independence of the error terms and the response.</em> Another assumption we
          want to check is the <em>I</em>ndependence of the response values. If data was
          collected in a time sequence, plotting residuals against time can help determine
          lack of independence. The <c>old_faithful_2024</c> dataset contains a <c>date</c>
          variable. <xref ref="fig-time-plot"/> shows the plot of residuals against date.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-time-plot">
          <caption>Scatterplot of date (time) vs residuals for the Old Faithful example.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-time-plot.png" width="80%">
            <description>Scatterplot of residuals on the y-axis versus date on the x-axis for the Old Faithful data, showing no systematic time-based pattern.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The plot of residuals against time seems to be a null plot. Based on this plot we
          could say that the residuals do not exhibit any evidence of dependency. Since we can
          consider this a random sample, the assumption of independence seems acceptable.
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Normality of the error terms.</em> The third assumption we want to check is
          whether the error terms follow <em>N</em>ormal distributions with expected value
          equal to zero. We can use a histogram and a <em>quantile-to-quantile (QQ) plot</em>
          of the residuals:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(fitted_and_residuals, aes(residual)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10, color = "white")
          </input>
        </program>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
fitted_and_residuals |>
  ggplot(aes(sample = residual)) +
  geom_qq() +
  geom_qq_line()
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          The QQ-plot creates a scatterplot of the quantiles of the residuals against the
          quantiles of a normal distribution. If the residuals follow approximately a normal
          distribution, the scatterplot would be a straight line of 45 degrees.
          <xref ref="fig-model1residualshist"/> shows both plots for <c>model_1</c>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-model1residualshist">
          <caption>Histogram of residuals (left) with normal curve overlay, and QQ-plot (right) for the Old Faithful regression.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-model1residualshist.png" width="90%">
            <description>Two plots side by side. Left: histogram of residuals with a normal distribution curve overlaid. Right: QQ-plot of residuals with a 45-degree reference line.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The histogram does not appear exactly normal but does not deviate much. The QQ-plot
          supports this conclusion. For comparison, <xref ref="fig-not-normal-residuals"/>
          shows residuals from a simulated model that clearly do not follow normality.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-not-normal-residuals">
          <caption>Example of clearly non-normal residuals (simulated data).</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-not-normal-residuals.png" width="90%">
            <description>Histogram and QQ-plot for simulated non-normal residuals, showing clear deviation from the normal distribution curve and from the 45-degree reference line.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <em>Equality or constancy of variance for errors.</em> The final assumption we check
          is the <em>E</em>quality or constancy of the variance —
          <term>homoskedasticity</term><idx><h>homoskedasticity</h></idx> — for the error term
          across all fitted values or regressor values. We check that the dispersion of the
          residuals is the same for any fitted value <m>\widehat{y}_i</m> or regressor
          <m>x_i</m>:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
ggplot(fitted_and_residuals, aes(x = duration, y = residual)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(x = "duration", y = "residual") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="fig-residual-plot-ch10">
          <caption>Plot of residuals against the regressor <c>duration</c>.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-residual-plot-ch10.png" width="80%">
            <description>Scatterplot of residuals on the y-axis versus eruption duration in seconds on the x-axis, with a horizontal reference line at zero.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          The spread of the residuals is not exactly constant across all values of
          <c>duration</c>, but there is not clear evidence against the assumption of
          homoskedasticity. For comparison, <xref ref="fig-equal-variance-residuals"/>
          shows a simulated example with non-constant variance.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-equal-variance-residuals">
          <caption>Example of clearly non-equal variance (simulated data).</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-equal-variance-residuals.png" width="75%">
            <description>Scatterplot of simulated residuals versus duration showing a fan-shaped pattern where the spread of residuals increases as the regressor value increases, illustrating heteroskedasticity.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Lack of constant variance is also known as
          <term>heteroskedasticity</term><idx><h>heteroskedasticity</h></idx>. When
          heteroskedasticity is present, the standard error of the least-square estimators,
          confidence intervals, or the conclusion for a related hypothesis test would not be
          valid.
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Conclusion.</em> For the Old Faithful data, we did not find conclusive evidence
          against any of the assumptions of the model: <em>L</em>inearity,
          <em>I</em>ndependence, <em>N</em>ormality, and <em>E</em>quality of variance.
          When there are clear violations, remedial measures include variable transformations
          for non-linearity, linear mixed-effects models for non-independence, and weighted
          least squares for non-constant variance. An example of such a variable transformation
          is given in <xref ref="appendix-log10-transformations"/>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Checking that the assumptions of the model are satisfied is a key component of
          regression analysis. It is important to highlight important elements that may suggest
          departures from relevant assumptions, and then provide pertinent conclusions.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-7">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the <c>un_member_states_2024</c> data frame included in the <c>moderndive</c>
              package with response variable fertility rate (<c>fertility_rate_2022</c>) and
              the regressor human development index (<c>hdi_2022</c>). Make sure to omit
              missing values.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><p>Use the <c>get_regression_points()</c> function to get the observed values, fitted values, and residuals for all UN member countries.</p></li>
              <li><p>Perform a residual analysis and look for any systematic patterns in the residuals. Ideally, there should be little to no pattern but comment on what you find.</p></li>
            </ul>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Fit the model and obtain residuals using:
            </p>
                        <program language="r">
              <input>
un_hdi &lt;- un_member_states_2024 |>
  select(fert_rate = fertility_rate_2022,
         hdi = hdi_2022) |>
  na.omit()
model_hdi &lt;- lm(fert_rate ~ hdi, data = un_hdi)
get_regression_points(model_hdi)
              </input>
            </program>

            <console prompt="> ">
              <output>
# A tibble: 184 × 5
      ID fert_rate   hdi fert_rate_hat residual
   &lt;int&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;         &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
 1     1       4.3 0.462          4.17    0.13 
 2     2       1.4 0.789          2.07   -0.667
 3     3       2.7 0.745          2.35    0.35 
 4     4       5   0.591          3.34    1.66 
 5     5       1.6 0.826          1.83   -0.229
 6     6       1.9 0.849          1.68    0.219
 7     7       1.6 0.786          2.09   -0.486
 8     8       1.6 0.946          1.06    0.543
 9     9       1.5 0.926          1.19    0.314
10    10       1.6 0.76           2.25   -0.654
# ℹ 174 more rows
              </output>
            </console>
            <p>
              The residual plot may show some non-random patterns (e.g., non-linearity or
              non-constant variance) suggesting that a simple linear model may not fully
              capture the relationship between fertility rate and HDI.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-8">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In the context of linear regression, a <c>p_value</c> of near zero for the
              slope coefficient suggests which of the following?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The intercept is statistically significant at a 95% confidence level.</p></li>
              <li><p>There is strong evidence against the null hypothesis that the slope coefficient is zero, suggesting there exists a linear relationship between the explanatory and response variables.</p></li>
              <li><p>The variance of the response variable is significantly greater than the variance of the explanatory variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>The residuals are normally distributed with mean zero and constant variance.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. A near-zero <m>p</m>-value for the slope coefficient provides strong evidence against the null hypothesis that <m>\beta_1 = 0</m>, indicating a linear relationship exists.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-9">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Explain whether or not the residual plot helps assess each one of the following
              assumptions.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><p>Linearity of the relationship between variables</p></li>
              <li><p>Independence of the error terms</p></li>
              <li><p>Normality of the error terms</p></li>
              <li><p>Equality or constancy of variance</p></li>
            </ul>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              The residual plot (residuals vs fitted values) directly helps assess:
              <em>Linearity</em> (look for non-linear patterns such as curves or U-shapes),
              <em>Equality of variance</em> (look for fan-shaped spread indicating
              heteroskedasticity). It can help assess <em>Independence</em> only when data are
              collected in a sequence (plot residuals vs time). It does <em>not</em> directly
              help assess <em>Normality</em>; for that, a histogram or QQ-plot of residuals is
              more appropriate.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-10">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the residual plot against fitted values shows a <q>U-shaped</q> pattern, what
              does this suggest?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The variance of the residuals is constant.</p></li>
              <li><p>The linearity assumption is violated.</p></li>
              <li><p>The independence assumption is violated.</p></li>
              <li><p>The normality assumption is satisfied.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. A U-shaped pattern in the residual plot suggests the linearity assumption is violated, indicating the relationship between the response and explanatory variable is non-linear.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Model fit and model assumptions -->

  </section><!-- end Theory-based inference for simple linear regression -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="infer-regression">
    <title>Simulation-based inference for simple linear regression</title>

    <p>
      In this section, we'll use the simulation-based methods you previously learned in
      <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> and <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/> to recreate
      the values in the regression table. In particular, we'll use the <c>infer</c> package
      workflow to
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Construct a 95% confidence interval for the population slope <m>\beta_1</m> using
          bootstrap resampling with replacement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Conduct a hypothesis test of <m>H_0: \beta_1 = 0</m> versus
          <m>H_A: \beta_1 \neq 0</m> using a permutation test.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <subsection xml:id="infer-ci-slr">
      <title>Confidence intervals for the population slope using <c>infer</c></title>

      <p>
        We'll construct a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> using the <c>infer</c>
        workflow. Specifically, we'll first construct the bootstrap distribution for the
        fitted slope <m>b_1</m> using our single sample of eruptions:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <c>specify()</c> the variables of interest in <c>old_faithful_2024</c> with
            the formula: <c>waiting ~ duration</c>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <c>generate()</c> replicates by using <c>bootstrap</c> resampling with
            replacement from the original sample. We generate
            <c>reps = 1000</c> replicates using <c>type = "bootstrap"</c>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <c>calculate()</c> the summary statistic of interest: the fitted <c>slope</c>
            <m>b_1</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        It is important to note in this case that the bootstrapping with replacement is done
        <em>row-by-row</em>. Thus, the original pairs of <c>waiting</c> and <c>duration</c>
        values are always kept together, but different pairs may be resampled multiple times.
        The resulting confidence interval will denote a range of plausible values for the
        unknown population slope <m>\beta_1</m>.
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
bootstrap_distn_slope &lt;- old_faithful_2024 |>
  specify(formula = waiting ~ duration) |>
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") |>
  calculate(stat = "slope")
bootstrap_distn_slope
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        Observe how we have 1000 values of the bootstrapped slope <m>b_1</m> in the
        <c>stat</c> column. We visualize these bootstrapped values in <xref ref="fig-bootstrap-distribution-slope"/>:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
visualize(bootstrap_distn_slope)
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-bootstrap-distribution-slope">
        <caption>Bootstrap distribution of slope for Old Faithful waiting and duration.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-bootstrap-distribution-slope.png" width="80%">
          <description>Histogram of 1000 bootstrapped slope estimates for the Old Faithful regression model, showing an approximately bell-shaped distribution centred near the observed slope.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Observe how the bootstrap distribution is roughly bell-shaped. Recall from <xref ref="revisit-almond-bootstrap"/> that the shape
        of the bootstrap distribution of <m>b_1</m> closely approximates the shape of the
        sampling distribution of <m>b_1</m>.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="percentile-ci-slr">
        <title>Percentile method</title>
        <p>
          First, let's compute the 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> using the
          percentile method. We identify the 2.5th and 97.5th percentiles which include the
          middle 95% of values. Recall that this method does not require the bootstrap
          distribution to be normally shaped.
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
percentile_ci &lt;- bootstrap_distn_slope |>
  get_confidence_interval(type = "percentile", level = 0.95)
percentile_ci
          </input>
        </program>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="se-ci-slr">
        <title>Standard error method</title>
        <p>
          Since the bootstrap distribution appears to be roughly bell-shaped, we can also
          construct a 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> using the standard error
          method. We first compute the fitted slope <m>b_1</m> using the <c>infer</c>
          pipeline with the <c>generate()</c> step removed:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
observed_slope &lt;- old_faithful_2024 |>
  specify(waiting ~ duration) |>
  calculate(stat = "slope")
observed_slope
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          We then use <c>get_ci()</c> with <c>level = 0.95</c> and set the
          <c>point_estimate</c> argument to the <c>observed_slope</c>:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
se_ci &lt;- bootstrap_distn_slope |>
  get_ci(level = 0.95, type = "se", point_estimate = observed_slope)
se_ci
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          The resulting standard error-based 95% confidence interval for <m>\beta_1</m> is
          slightly different than the percentile-based confidence interval. Note that neither
          of these confidence intervals contains 0 and both are entirely located above 0,
          suggesting a meaningful positive relationship between waiting times and duration
          for Old Faithful eruptions.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

    </subsection><!-- end Confidence intervals using infer -->


    <subsection xml:id="infer-hypo-slr">
      <title>Hypothesis test for population slope using <c>infer</c></title>

      <p>
        Let's conduct a hypothesis test of <m>H_0: \beta_1 = 0</m> vs.
        <m>H_A: \beta_1 \neq 0</m>. Recall that if <m>\beta_1 = 0</m>, there is no
        relationship between waiting time and duration. We can therefore
        shuffle/permute the <c>waiting</c> variable with no consequence.
      </p>
      <p>
        We construct the null distribution of the fitted slope <m>b_1</m> by:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p><c>specify()</c> the variables of interest with the formula: <c>waiting ~ duration</c>.</p></li>
        <li><p><c>hypothesize()</c> the null hypothesis of <c>independence</c>.</p></li>
        <li><p><c>generate()</c> <c>reps = 1000</c> replicates by permuting/shuffling values using <c>type = "permute"</c>.</p></li>
        <li><p><c>calculate()</c> the test statistic: the fitted <c>slope</c> <m>b_1</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
null_distn_slope &lt;- old_faithful_2024 |>
  specify(waiting ~ duration) |>
  hypothesize(null = "independence") |>
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") |>
  calculate(stat = "slope")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-null-distribution-slope">
        <caption>Null distribution of slopes for the Old Faithful hypothesis test.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-null-distribution-slope.png" width="80%">
          <description>Histogram of the null distribution of 1000 permuted slope estimates, centred at zero, used to test whether the population slope is zero.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Notice from <xref ref="fig-null-distribution-slope"/> how it is centered at <m>b_1 = 0</m>. This is because in our hypothesized
        universe, there is no relationship between <c>waiting</c> and <c>duration</c> and
        so <m>\beta_1 = 0</m>. We obtain the observed slope:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
b1 &lt;- old_faithful_2024 |>
  specify(waiting ~ duration) |>
  calculate(stat = "slope")
b1
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        We visualize the <m>p</m>-value in <xref ref="fig-p-value-slope"/> by shading the null distribution and comparing to
        the observed test statistic:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
visualize(null_distn_slope) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = b1, direction = "both")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-p-value-slope">
        <caption>Null distribution and <m>p</m>-value for the Old Faithful slope test.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-p-value-slope.png" width="80%">
          <description>Null distribution of permuted slopes with the observed slope highlighted as a vertical line far to the right of the distribution, illustrating a p-value of approximately zero.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Since the observed fitted slope falls far to the right of this null distribution,
        we compute the numerical <m>p</m>-value:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
null_distn_slope |>
  get_p_value(obs_stat = b1, direction = "both")
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        The <m>p</m>-value is 0, matching the regression table. We therefore reject the
        null hypothesis <m>H_0: \beta_1 = 0</m> in favor of the alternative
        <m>H_A: \beta_1 \neq 0</m>. We have evidence that suggests there is a significant
        relationship between waiting time and duration values for eruptions of Old Faithful.
        When the conditions for inference are met and the null distribution has a bell shape,
        we expect similar results from simulation-based and theory-based approaches.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-11">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Repeat the inference but this time for the correlation coefficient instead of
              the slope. Note the implementation of <c>stat = "correlation"</c> in the
              <c>calculate()</c> function of the <c>infer</c> package.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Replace <c>stat = "slope"</c> with <c>stat = "correlation"</c> in both the
              bootstrap and null-distribution pipelines. The resulting confidence interval
              and <m>p</m>-value should be consistent with those obtained for the slope,
              since the two statistics carry equivalent information about the linear
              relationship.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-12">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Why is it appropriate to use the bootstrap percentile method to construct a 95%
              confidence interval for the population slope <m>\beta_1</m> in the Old Faithful
              data?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>Because it assumes the slope follows a perfect normal distribution.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because it relies on resampling the residuals instead of the original data points.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because it requires the original data to be uniformly distributed.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because it does not require the bootstrap distribution to be normally shaped.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>D. The percentile method does not require the bootstrap distribution to be normally shaped, making it applicable in a wider range of situations.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-13">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the role of the permutation test in the hypothesis testing for the
              population slope <m>\beta_1</m>?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>It generates new samples to confirm the confidence interval boundaries.</p></li>
              <li><p>It assesses whether the observed slope could have occurred by chance under the null hypothesis of no relationship.</p></li>
              <li><p>It adjusts the sample size to reduce sampling variability.</p></li>
              <li><p>It ensures the residuals of the regression model are normally distributed.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. The permutation test shuffles the response variable to simulate a world where there is no relationship, and then measures how extreme the observed slope is relative to the resulting null distribution.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-14">
          <statement>
            <p>
              After generating a null distribution for the slope using <c>infer</c>, you find
              the <m>p</m>-value to be near 0. What does this indicate about the relationship
              between <c>waiting</c> and <c>duration</c> in the Old Faithful data?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>There is no evidence of a relationship between <c>waiting</c> and <c>duration</c>.</p></li>
              <li><p>The observed slope is likely due to random variation under the null hypothesis.</p></li>
              <li><p>The observed slope is significantly different from zero, suggesting a meaningful relationship between <c>waiting</c> and <c>duration</c>.</p></li>
              <li><p>The null hypothesis cannot be rejected because the <m>p</m>-value is too small.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. A near-zero <m>p</m>-value means the observed slope is very unlikely under the null hypothesis, providing strong evidence of a meaningful relationship.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Hypothesis test using infer -->

  </section><!-- end Simulation-based inference for SLR -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="multiple-linear-regression-model">
    <title>The multiple linear regression model</title>

    <subsection xml:id="multiple-linear-model">
      <title>The model</title>

      <p>
        The extension from a simple to a multiple regression model is discussed next.
        We assume that a population has a response variable (<m>Y</m>) and two or more
        explanatory variables (<m>X_1, X_2, \dots, X_p</m>) with <m>p \ge 2</m>.
        The statistical linear relationship between these variables is given by
      </p>
      <me>
        Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X_1 + \dots + \beta_p X_p + \epsilon
      </me>
      <p>
        where <m>\beta_0</m> is the population intercept and <m>\beta_j</m> is the population
        partial slope related to regressor <m>X_j</m>. The error term <m>\epsilon</m>
        accounts for the portion of <m>Y</m> not explained by the regressors. As in the
        simple case, we assume <m>E(\epsilon) = 0</m>, <m>SD(\epsilon) = \sigma</m>, and
        <m>Var(\epsilon) = \sigma^2</m> constant regardless of the values of the regressors.
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="coffee-example">
      <title>Example: coffee quality rating scores</title>

      <p>
        To illustrate multiple regression, we use the <c>coffee_quality</c> data frame from
        the <c>moderndive</c> package. This dataset from the Coffee Quality Institute contains
        information about coffee rating scores based on ten different attributes:
        <c>aroma</c>, <c>flavor</c>, <c>aftertaste</c>, <c>acidity</c>, <c>body</c>,
        <c>balance</c>, <c>uniformity</c>, <c>clean_cup</c>, <c>sweetness</c>, and
        <c>overall</c>. In addition, the data frame contains information such as the
        <c>moisture_percentage</c> and the coffee's <c>country</c> and
        <c>continent_of_origin</c>. We can assume that this is a random sample.
      </p>
      <p>
        We plan to regress <c>total_cup_points</c> (response variable) on the numerical
        explanatory variables <c>aroma</c>, <c>flavor</c>, and <c>moisture_percentage</c>
        and the categorical explanatory variable <c>continent_of_origin</c> with four
        categories: <c>Africa</c>, <c>Asia</c>, <c>North America</c>, and
        <c>South America</c>. Before proceeding, we construct a new data frame called
        <c>coffee_data</c>:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
coffee_data &lt;- coffee_quality |>
  select(aroma,
         flavor,
         moisture_percentage,
         continent_of_origin,
         total_cup_points) |>
  mutate(continent_of_origin = as.factor(continent_of_origin))
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        We display the summary for these variables:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
coffee_data |>
  tidy_summary()
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 8 × 11
  column               n group type    min    Q1  mean median    Q3   max     sd
  &lt;chr&gt;            &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;chr&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;dbl&gt;  &lt;dbl&gt;
1 aroma              207 &lt;NA&gt;  nume…  6.5   7.58  7.72   7.67  7.92  8.58  0.288
2 flavor             207 &lt;NA&gt;  nume…  6.75  7.58  7.74   7.75  7.92  8.5   0.280
3 moisture_percen…   207 &lt;NA&gt;  nume…  0    10.1  10.7   10.8  11.5  13.5   1.25 
4 total_cup_points   207 &lt;NA&gt;  nume… 78    82.6  83.7   83.8  84.8  89.3   1.73 
5 continent_of_or…    23 Afri… fact… NA    NA    NA     NA    NA    NA    NA    
6 continent_of_or…    84 Asia  fact… NA    NA    NA     NA    NA    NA    NA    
7 continent_of_or…    67 Nort… fact… NA    NA    NA     NA    NA    NA    NA    
8 continent_of_or…    33 Sout… fact… NA    NA    NA     NA    NA    NA    NA
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        When performing multiple regression it is useful to construct a
        <term>scatterplot matrix</term><idx><h>scatterplot matrix</h></idx>, a matrix that
        contains scatterplots for all variable pair combinations. In R, we use
        <c>ggpairs()</c> from the <c>GGally</c> package (<xref ref="fig-coffee-scatter-matrix"/>):
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
coffee_data |>
  ggpairs()
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-coffee-scatter-matrix">
        <caption>Scatterplot matrix for coffee quality variables of interest.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-coffee-scatter-matrix.png" width="90%">
          <description>A scatterplot matrix showing relationships between aroma, flavor, moisture_percentage, continent_of_origin, and total_cup_points for the coffee quality dataset. Strong positive associations are visible between total_cup_points and both aroma and flavor.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        We first comment on the plots with the response (<c>total_cup_points</c>) on the
        vertical axis. When plotting <c>total_cup_points</c> against <c>aroma</c> or
        <c>total_cup_points</c> against <c>flavor</c>, we observe a strong and positive
        linear relationship. The plot of <c>total_cup_points</c> against
        <c>moisture_percentage</c> does not provide much information. The
        <c>ggpairs()</c> function also includes the correlation coefficient for any pair of
        numerical variables. The correlations between <c>total_cup_points</c> and
        <c>aroma</c> and <c>flavor</c> are positive and close to one. The correlation
        between <c>moisture_percentage</c> and any other variable is close to zero.
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="least-squares-multiple">
      <title>Least squares for multiple regression</title>

      <p>
        We have three numerical regressors and one factor (<c>continent_of_origin</c>) with
        four levels: <c>"Africa"</c>, <c>"Asia"</c>, <c>"North America"</c>, and
        <c>"South America"</c>. To introduce the factor levels in the linear model, we
        represent them using dummy variables. We need:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>D_1 &amp;= 1 \text{ if Africa, } 0 \text{ otherwise}</mrow>
        <mrow>D_2 &amp;= 1 \text{ if Asia, } 0 \text{ otherwise}</mrow>
        <mrow>D_3 &amp;= 1 \text{ if North America, } 0 \text{ otherwise}</mrow>
        <mrow>D_4 &amp;= 1 \text{ if South America, } 0 \text{ otherwise}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Recall that we drop the first level (<c>Africa</c>) as it is accounted for by the
        intercept. The linear model for the <m>i</m>th observation is:
      </p>
      <me>
        y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2} + \beta_3 x_{i3}
              + \beta_{02}D_{i2} + \beta_{03}D_{i3} + \beta_{04}D_{i4} + \epsilon_i
      </me>
      <p>
        where <m>x_{i1}</m> is <c>aroma</c>, <m>x_{i2}</m> is <c>flavor</c>,
        <m>x_{i3}</m> is <c>moisture_percentage</c>, and <m>D_{i2}</m>, <m>D_{i3}</m>,
        <m>D_{i4}</m> are the dummy variables for <c>Asia</c>, <c>North America</c>, and
        <c>South America</c>, respectively.
      </p>
      <p>
        We want the coefficient estimators that minimize the <em>sum of squared residuals</em>:
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{i=1}^n \left[y_i - (\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \beta_2 x_{i2}
        + \beta_3 x_{i3}+ \beta_{02}D_{i2} + \beta_{03}D_{i3} + \beta_{04}D_{i4})\right]^2.
      </me>
      <p>
        These are the <term>least-squares estimators</term> for multiple regression. The
        fitted values, residuals, and model standard deviation are direct extensions of
        those in the simple linear case:
      </p>
      <me>
        \widehat{y}_i = b_0 + b_1 x_{i1} + b_2 x_{i2} + \dots + b_p x_{ip},
        \quad
        e_i = y_i - \widehat{y}_i,
        \quad
        s^2 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \widehat{y}_i)^2}{n - p}.
      </me>
      <p>
        In R, all these calculations are done when using the <c>lm()</c> function:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
# Fit regression model:
mod_mult &lt;- lm(
  total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage + continent_of_origin,
  data = coffee_data
)

# Get the coefficients and standard deviation of the model
coef(mod_mult)
sigma(mod_mult)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
[1] 0.5066865
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        Recall that the numerical regressors' coefficients (<m>b_1</m>, <m>b_2</m>, and
        <m>b_3</m>) are partial slopes, each representing the extra effect of increasing the
        corresponding regressor by one unit while keeping all other regressors fixed. For
        example, if we increase the <c>flavor</c> score by one unit keeping all other
        regressors fixed, the <c>total_cup_points</c> would increase by the corresponding
        coefficient, on average. This interpretation is only valid for this particular model.
        If we change the regressors used, the partial slope for <c>flavor</c> will be
        different in magnitude and meaning.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-15">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In a multiple linear regression model, what does the coefficient
              <m>\beta_j</m> represent?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The intercept of the model.</p></li>
              <li><p>The standard error of the estimate.</p></li>
              <li><p>The total variance explained by the model.</p></li>
              <li><p>The partial slope related to the regressor <m>X_j</m>, accounting for all other regressors.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>D. <m>\beta_j</m> is the partial slope for <m>X_j</m>: the expected change in <m>Y</m> per one-unit increase in <m>X_j</m> with all other regressors held constant.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-16">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Why is it necessary to convert <c>continent_of_origin</c> to a factor when
              preparing the <c>coffee_data</c> data frame for regression analysis?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>To allow the regression model to interpret <c>continent_of_origin</c> as a numerical variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>To create dummy variables that represent different categories of <c>continent_of_origin</c>.</p></li>
              <li><p>To reduce the number of observations in the dataset.</p></li>
              <li><p>To ensure the variable is included in the correlation matrix.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. Converting to a factor allows R to automatically create dummy variables for each level of the categorical variable.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-17">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the purpose of creating a scatterplot matrix in the context of
              multiple linear regression?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>To identify outliers that need to be removed from the dataset.</p></li>
              <li><p>To test for normality of the residuals.</p></li>
              <li><p>To examine linear relationships between all variable pairs and identify multicollinearity among regressors.</p></li>
              <li><p>To determine the appropriate number of dummy variables.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. The scatterplot matrix reveals pairwise relationships and potential multicollinearity between regressors, informing model-building decisions.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-18">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In the multiple regression model for <c>coffee_data</c>, what is the role of
              dummy variables for <c>continent_of_origin</c>?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>They are used to predict the values of the numerical regressors.</p></li>
              <li><p>They modify the intercept based on the specific category of <c>continent_of_origin</c>.</p></li>
              <li><p>They serve to test the independence of residuals.</p></li>
              <li><p>They indicate which observations should be excluded from the model.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. Dummy variables for a factor shift the intercept up or down based on the category of each observation, creating parallel regression lines for each group.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Least squares for multiple regression -->

  </section><!-- end The multiple linear regression model -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="theory-multiple-regression">
    <title>Theory-based inference for multiple linear regression</title>

    <p>
      In this section, we introduce the conceptual framework for inference in multiple linear
      regression. Inference for multiple linear regression is a natural extension of inference
      for simple linear regression. Recall the linear model for the <m>i</m>th observation:
    </p>
    <me>
      y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_{i1} + \dots + \beta_p x_{ip} + \epsilon_i.
    </me>
    <p>
      We again assume the error term is normally distributed:
      <m>\epsilon_i \sim \text{Normal}(0, \sigma)</m>.
      It follows that:
    </p>
    <me>
      y_i \sim \text{Normal}(\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot x_{i1} + \dots + \beta_p x_{ip},\, \sigma)
    </me>
    <p>
      for <m>i=1,\dots,n</m>. The least-squares estimators <m>b_0, b_1, \dots, b_p</m> are
      linear combinations of normally distributed random variables, so they are also normally
      distributed. The standard deviation of each estimator <m>b_j</m> is a function of
      <m>\sigma</m> and the observed data; when we estimate <m>\sigma</m> with <m>s</m>, the
      resulting estimated standard deviation is called the <term>standard error</term>
      <m>SE(b_j)</m>. The regression table produced by
      <c>get_regression_table()</c> contains these standard errors:
    </p>
        <program language="r">
      <input>
get_regression_table(mod_mult)
      </input>
    </program>

    <console prompt="> ">
      <output>
# A tibble: 7 × 7
  term                    estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;                      &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept                 37.3       1.12      33.4    0       35.1     39.5  
2 aroma                      1.73      0.222      7.80   0        1.29     2.17 
3 flavor                     4.32      0.226     19.1    0        3.87     4.76 
4 moisture_percentage       -0.008     0.03      -0.27   0.787   -0.067    0.051
5 continent_of_origin-As…   -0.393     0.121     -3.24   0.001   -0.632   -0.154
6 continent_of_origin-No…   -0.273     0.127     -2.15   0.033   -0.524   -0.023
7 continent_of_origin-So…   -0.478     0.142     -3.38   0.001   -0.757   -0.199
      </output>
    </console>


    <subsection xml:id="model-dependency">
      <title>Model dependency of estimators</title>

      <p>
        The most important difference between multiple and simple linear regression inference
        is that the least-squares estimators represent <em>partial</em> slopes whose values
        depend on the other regressors in the model. If we change the set of regressors, the
        least-squares estimates and their standard errors will likely change as well, leading
        to different confidence intervals, different test statistics, and potentially different
        conclusions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using the <c>coffee_data</c> example, suppose we consider a model with only three
        numerical regressors (dropping <c>continent_of_origin</c>):
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
# Model with three numerical regressors:
mod_mult_1 &lt;- lm(
  total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage,
  data = coffee_data)
coef(mod_mult_1)
sigma(mod_mult_1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
[1] 0.5208255
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        Now consider a further reduced model without the regressor <c>flavor</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
# Model without flavor:
mod_mult_2 &lt;- lm(
  total_cup_points ~ aroma + moisture_percentage, data = coffee_data)
coef(mod_mult_2)
sigma(mod_mult_2)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
[1] 0.8571982
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The partial slope for <c>aroma</c> in <c>mod_mult_1</c> differs from the partial
        slope for <c>aroma</c> in <c>mod_mult_2</c> because the models are different.
        Similarly, every other coefficient, the standard deviation estimate, and inferential
        results can differ. Any results and interpretations are only valid for the model
        used — never assume a conclusion from one model translates to a different model.
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="ci-multiple-regression">
      <title>Confidence intervals</title>

      <p>
        A 95% confidence interval for any coefficient in multiple linear regression is
        constructed in exactly the same way as for simple linear regression:
        <m>b_j \pm q \cdot SE(b_j)</m>, where the critical value <m>q</m> is determined
        by the confidence level and degrees of freedom <m>n - p</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the coffee example with model <c>mod_mult</c>: three numerical regressors,
        one four-level factor (three dummy variables), and an intercept give
        <m>p = 7</m> coefficients. The 95% CI for the partial slope of <c>aroma</c>
        (<m>\beta_1</m>) is:
      </p>
      <me>
        b_1 \pm q \cdot SE(b_1).
      </me>
      <p>
        We can compute 98% confidence intervals for all coefficients by passing
        <c>conf.level = 0.98</c> to <c>get_regression_table()</c>:
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
get_regression_table(mod_mult, conf.level = 0.98)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 7 × 7
  term                    estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;                      &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept                 37.3       1.12      33.4    0       34.7     39.9  
2 aroma                      1.73      0.222      7.80   0        1.21     2.25 
3 flavor                     4.32      0.226     19.1    0        3.79     4.85 
4 moisture_percentage       -0.008     0.03      -0.27   0.787   -0.078    0.062
5 continent_of_origin-As…   -0.393     0.121     -3.24   0.001   -0.678   -0.108
6 continent_of_origin-No…   -0.273     0.127     -2.15   0.033   -0.571    0.025
7 continent_of_origin-So…   -0.478     0.142     -3.38   0.001   -0.81    -0.146
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The interpretation for the <c>flavor</c> coefficient, for example, is: <q>We are 98%
        confident that the value of <m>\beta_2</m> (the population partial slope for
        <c>flavor</c>) is between the reported lower and upper bounds.</q>
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="hypo-test-mult-lm">
      <title>Hypothesis test for a single coefficient</title>

      <p>
        The hypothesis test for one coefficient, say <m>\beta_j</m>, is similar to that for
        simple linear regression. The general two-sided test is:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>H_0&amp;: \beta_j = 0 \quad \text{with all other parameters given and arbitrary}</mrow>
        <mrow>H_A&amp;: \beta_j \ne 0 \quad \text{with all other parameters given and arbitrary.}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        In simple linear regression, testing <m>\beta_1 = 0</m> was testing whether there
        was a linear relationship between the response and the only regressor. Now, testing
        <m>\beta_j = 0</m> is testing whether the corresponding regressor should be part of
        a linear model that already contains all the other regressors.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, using model <c>mod_mult_1</c> and testing <m>\beta_2 = 0</m>
        (the partial slope for <c>flavor</c>):
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
get_regression_table(mod_mult_1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
# A tibble: 4 × 7
  term                estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  &lt;chr&gt;                  &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1 intercept             36.8       1.10     33.6     0       34.6     38.9  
2 aroma                  1.8       0.223     8.09    0        1.36     2.24 
3 flavor                 4.28      0.229    18.7     0        3.83     4.74 
4 moisture_percentage   -0.015     0.029    -0.499   0.618   -0.072    0.043
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The <m>t</m>-test statistic is <m>t = b_2 / SE(b_2)</m>; the associated
        <m>p</m>-value is near zero, so we reject <m>H_0</m> and conclude that
        <c>flavor</c> is statistically significant when added to a model that already
        contains <c>aroma</c> and <c>moisture_percentage</c>. By contrast, <c>moisture_percentage</c>
        is not statistically significant in that model, suggesting we can remove it.
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="hypo-test-mult-lm-1">
      <title>Hypothesis test for model comparison</title>

      <p>
        There is another hypothesis test for multiple linear regression: comparing a
        <em>full model</em> with a given set of regressors to a <em>reduced model</em> that
        uses only a subset of those regressors. This test is called an
        <term>ANOVA test</term><idx><h>ANOVA test</h></idx> or <m>F</m>-test, because the
        test statistic follows an <m>F</m> distribution.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using <c>coffee_data</c>, compare the full model <c>mod_mult_1</c>
        (<c>aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage</c>) to the reduced model <c>mod_mult_2</c>
        (<c>aroma + moisture_percentage</c>):
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>H_0&amp;: \text{the reduced model is adequate}</mrow>
        <mrow>H_A&amp;: \text{the full model is needed.}</mrow>
      </md>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
anova(mod_mult_2, mod_mult_1)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
Analysis of Variance Table

Model 1: total_cup_points ~ aroma + moisture_percentage
Model 2: total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage
  Res.Df     RSS Df Sum of Sq     F    Pr(&gt;F)    
1    204 149.897                                 
2    203  55.066  1    94.831 349.6 &lt; 2.2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        The small <m>p</m>-value leads us to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the
        full model (including <c>flavor</c>) was needed.
      </p>
      <p>
        The ANOVA test can test more than one regressor at a time, which is especially useful
        for factors. To test whether <c>continent_of_origin</c> should be included, compare
        <c>mod_mult_1</c> (without the factor) to <c>mod_mult</c> (with the factor):
      </p>
            <program language="r">
        <input>
anova(mod_mult_1, mod_mult)
        </input>
      </program>

      <console prompt="> ">
        <output>
Analysis of Variance Table

Model 1: total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage
Model 2: total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage + continent_of_origin
  Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F   Pr(&gt;F)   
1    203 55.066                                
2    200 51.346  3    3.7194 4.8292 0.002876 **
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1
        </output>
      </console>
      <p>
        We reject the null hypothesis and conclude that it is appropriate to add
        <c>continent_of_origin</c> to a model that already has <c>aroma</c>, <c>flavor</c>,
        and <c>moisture_percentage</c>. When testing factors in ANOVA, all factor levels must
        always be tested simultaneously.
      </p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="model-fit-mult">
      <title>Model fit and diagnostics</title>

      <p>
        As for simple linear regression, we use residuals to determine the fit of the model
        and whether assumptions are met. In particular, the plot of residuals against the
        fitted values should look like a null plot. In multiple regression, when the
        residual-vs-fitted plot shows a pattern, we know that at least one assumption is
        violated, though it is no longer immediately clear which one.
      </p>
      <p>
        Using the coffee example, we have shown that <c>aroma</c>, <c>flavor</c>, and
        <c>continent_of_origin</c> were statistically significant but <c>moisture_percentage</c>
        was not. We create a final model <c>mod_mult_final</c> with only the relevant
        regressors and examine residuals:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
# Fit final model:
mod_mult_final &lt;- lm(total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + continent_of_origin,
                     coffee_data)
# Get fitted values and residuals:
fit_and_res_mult &lt;- get_regression_points(mod_mult_final)
        </input>
      </program>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
g1 &lt;- fit_and_res_mult |>
  ggplot(aes(x = total_cup_points_hat, y = residual)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "fitted values (total cup points)", y = "residual") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "blue")
g2 &lt;- ggplot(fit_and_res_mult, aes(sample = residual)) +
  geom_qq() +
  geom_qq_line(col = "blue", linewidth = 0.5)
grid.arrange(g1, g2, ncol = 2)
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-grid-arrange-plot-check">
        <caption>Residuals vs. fitted values and QQ-plot for the multiple regression model.</caption>
        <image source="images/fig-grid-arrange-plot-check.png" width="90%">
          <description>Two side-by-side plots for the final coffee quality regression model. Left: residuals versus fitted total cup points with a horizontal blue line at zero showing no clear pattern. Right: QQ-plot of residuals against theoretical normal quantiles showing approximate normality.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The plot of residuals against fitted values (left) in <xref ref="fig-grid-arrange-plot-check"/> appears to be close to a null
        plot, supporting the <em>L</em>inearity condition. The <em>E</em>qual or constant
        variance also holds as the vertical dispersion is fairly uniform. Since we assumed
        the data were collected randomly with no time sequence, the assumption of
        <em>I</em>ndependence is acceptable. The QQ-plot suggests (with the exception of one
        or two observations) that the residuals follow approximately the normal distribution.
        We can conclude that this model holds the assumptions well.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-19">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Why is it essential to know that the estimators
              <m>b_0, b_1, \dots, b_p</m> in multiple linear regression are unbiased?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>It ensures that the variance of the estimators is always zero.</p></li>
              <li><p>It means that, on average, the estimators will equal the true population parameters they estimate.</p></li>
              <li><p>It implies that the estimators have a standard error of zero.</p></li>
              <li><p>It suggests that the regression model will always have a perfect fit.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. Unbiasedness means that over many random samples, the average value of each estimator equals the true population parameter.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-20">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Why do the least-squares estimates of coefficients change when different sets
              of regressors are used in multiple linear regression?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>Because the coefficients are recalculated each time, irrespective of the regressors.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because the residuals are always zero when regressors are changed.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because the value of each coefficient depends on the specific combination of regressors included in the model.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because all models with different regressors produce identical estimates.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. Each partial slope coefficient represents the contribution of its regressor after accounting for all others; changing which others are included changes that contribution.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-21">
          <statement>
            <p>
              How is a 95% confidence interval for a coefficient in multiple linear
              regression constructed?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>By using the point estimate, the critical value from the <m>t</m>-distribution, and the standard error of the coefficient.</p></li>
              <li><p>By taking the standard deviation of the coefficients only.</p></li>
              <li><p>By resampling the data without replacement.</p></li>
              <li><p>By calculating the mean of all the coefficients.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>A. A 95% CI is <m>b_j \pm q \cdot SE(b_j)</m>, where <m>q</m> is the critical value from the <m>t</m>-distribution with <m>n - p</m> degrees of freedom.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-22">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What does the ANOVA <m>F</m>-test for comparing two models in multiple linear
              regression evaluate?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>Whether all regressors in both models have the same coefficients.</p></li>
              <li><p>Whether the reduced model is adequate or if the full model is needed.</p></li>
              <li><p>Whether the residuals of the two models follow a normal distribution.</p></li>
              <li><p>Whether the regression coefficients of one model are unbiased estimators.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. The ANOVA <m>F</m>-test compares the sum of squared residuals of the full and reduced models to determine whether the additional regressors in the full model provide a significantly better fit.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end Model fit and diagnostics -->

  </section><!-- end Theory-based inference for MLR -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="simulation-inference-mlr">
    <title>Simulation-based inference for multiple linear regression</title>

    <subsection xml:id="ci-mlr-infer">
      <title>Confidence intervals for the partial slopes using <c>infer</c></title>

      <p>
        We'll now use simulation-based methods to compute ranges of plausible values for
        partial slopes with multiple linear regression. We'll use the <c>infer</c> package
        as in <xref ref="infer-regression"/>, but this time using the <c>fit()</c> function.
      </p>

      <subsubsection xml:id="observed-fit-mlr">
        <title>Getting the observed fitted model</title>
        <p>
          We retrieve the observed coefficients using the <c>specify()</c> function combined
          with <c>fit()</c>:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
observed_fit &lt;- coffee_data |>
  specify(
    total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage + continent_of_origin
  ) |>
  fit()
observed_fit
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          These values match the first two columns of the <c>get_regression_table()</c> output
          for <c>mod_mult</c>. The <c>observed_fit</c> values will be our point estimates for
          the partial slopes in the confidence intervals.
        </p>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="bootstrap-mlr">
        <title>Bootstrap distribution for the partial slopes</title>
        <p>
          We find the bootstrap distribution for the partial slopes using the <c>infer</c>
          workflow. We resample entire rows to construct the bootstrap distribution:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><c>specify()</c> the formula: <c>total_cup_points ~ aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage + continent_of_origin</c>.</p></li>
          <li><p><c>generate()</c> 1000 bootstrap replicates with <c>type = "bootstrap"</c>.</p></li>
          <li><p><c>fit()</c> models for each replicate.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
boot_distribution_mlr &lt;- coffee_quality |>
  specify(
    total_cup_points ~ continent_of_origin + aroma + flavor + moisture_percentage
  ) |>
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "bootstrap") |>
  fit()
boot_distribution_mlr
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          Since we have 7 coefficients (intercept, 3 dummy variables for
          <c>continent_of_origin</c>, <c>aroma</c>, <c>flavor</c>,
          <c>moisture_percentage</c>), we have 7 rows for each replicate giving
          7,000 rows in <c>boot_distribution_mlr</c>. We can visualize the bootstrap
          distributions in <xref ref="fig-boot-distn-slopes"/>:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
visualize(boot_distribution_mlr)
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="fig-boot-distn-slopes">
          <caption>Bootstrap distributions of partial slopes for the coffee quality multiple regression.</caption>
          <image source="images/boot_mlr_viz.png" width="75%">
            <description>Faceted histogram showing bootstrap distributions for each of the 7 coefficients in the multiple linear regression model for coffee quality, including the intercept, three continent dummy variables, and three numerical regressors.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </subsubsection>

      <subsubsection xml:id="ci-mlr-percentile">
        <title>Confidence intervals for the partial slopes</title>
        <p>
          We construct 95% confidence intervals using the percentile-based method:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
confidence_intervals_mlr &lt;- boot_distribution_mlr |>
  get_confidence_interval(
    level = 0.95,
    type = "percentile",
    point_estimate = observed_fit)
confidence_intervals_mlr
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          The confidence intervals for <c>aroma</c> and <c>flavor</c> do not include 0,
          suggesting they are statistically significant and have a meaningful and reliable
          impact on the response. The confidence interval for <c>moisture_percentage</c>
          includes 0, again providing evidence that it might not be a useful regressor in
          this model. We visualize these confidence intervals in <xref ref="fig-ci-slopes-multiple"/>:
        </p>
        <program language="r">
          <input>
visualize(boot_distribution_mlr) +
  shade_confidence_interval(endpoints = confidence_intervals_mlr)
          </input>
        </program>

        <figure xml:id="fig-ci-slopes-multiple">
          <caption>95% confidence intervals for the partial slopes from the coffee quality regression.</caption>
          <image source="images/fig-ci-slopes-multiple.png" width="75%">
            <description>Faceted histograms of bootstrap distributions for each coefficient with shaded 95% confidence interval regions. The confidence intervals for aroma and flavor do not include zero, while that for moisture_percentage does.</description>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </subsubsection>

    </subsection><!-- end CI for partial slopes using infer -->


    <subsection xml:id="ht-mlr-infer">
      <title>Hypothesis testing for the partial slopes using <c>infer</c></title>

      <p>
        We can also conduct hypothesis tests for the partial slopes using permutation tests
        to test <m>H_0: \beta_j = 0</m> vs. <m>H_A: \beta_j \neq 0</m> for each partial
        slope. The syntax is similar to constructing the bootstrap distribution, but we use
        <c>type = "permute"</c> and set <c>hypothesize</c> to <c>null = "independence"</c>:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
set.seed(2024)
null_distribution_mlr &lt;- coffee_quality |>
  specify(total_cup_points ~ continent_of_origin + aroma +
      flavor + moisture_percentage) |>
  hypothesize(null = "independence") |>
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") |>
  fit()
null_distribution_mlr
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        We visualize the <m>p</m>-values by shading the null distributions:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
visualize(null_distribution_mlr) +
  shade_p_value(obs_stat = observed_fit, direction = "two-sided")
        </input>
      </program>

      <figure xml:id="fig-shaded-p-values-partial">
        <caption>Shaded <m>p</m>-values for the partial slopes in the multiple regression model.</caption>
        <image source="images/mlr_pvalue_viz.png" width="75%">
          <description>Faceted histograms showing null distributions for each coefficient with shaded p-value regions. For aroma and flavor, the observed test statistics fall far to the right of the null distribution. For moisture_percentage, the observed statistic falls within the null distribution.</description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        From these visualizations (<xref ref="fig-shaded-p-values-partial"/>), <c>aroma</c> and <c>flavor</c> are statistically
        significant, as their observed test statistics fall far to the right of the null
        distribution. On the other hand, <c>moisture_percentage</c> is not statistically
        significant. We compute the numerical <m>p</m>-values:
      </p>
      <program language="r">
        <input>
null_distribution_mlr |>
  get_p_value(obs_stat = observed_fit, direction = "two-sided")
        </input>
      </program>
      <p>
        These results match our findings from the visualizations and the regression table.
        We reject the null hypothesis <m>H_0: \beta_j = 0</m> for <c>aroma</c> and
        <c>flavor</c>, but fail to reject it for <c>moisture_percentage</c>.
      </p>

      <exercises>
        <exercise xml:id="lc10-23">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Why might one prefer to use simulation-based methods (e.g., bootstrapping) for
              inference in multiple linear regression?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>Because simulation-based methods require larger sample sizes than theory-based methods.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because simulation-based methods are always faster to compute than theory-based methods.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because simulation-based methods guarantee the correct model is used.</p></li>
              <li><p>Because simulation-based methods do not rely on the assumptions of normality or large sample sizes.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>D. Simulation-based methods relax the normality assumption, making them preferable when model assumptions are uncertain or small samples are involved.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-24">
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the purpose of constructing a bootstrap distribution for the partial
              slopes in multiple linear regression?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>To replace the original data with random numbers.</p></li>
              <li><p>To approximate the sampling distribution of the partial slopes by resampling with replacement.</p></li>
              <li><p>To calculate the exact values of the coefficients in the population.</p></li>
              <li><p>To test if the model assumptions are violated.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>B. Bootstrap resampling approximates the sampling distribution of each partial slope, allowing confidence intervals to be constructed without strong distributional assumptions.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-25">
          <statement>
            <p>
              If a 95% confidence interval for a partial slope in multiple linear regression
              includes 0, what does this suggest about the variable?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The variable does not have a statistically significant relationship with the response variable.</p></li>
              <li><p>The variable is statistically significant.</p></li>
              <li><p>The variable's coefficient estimate is always negative.</p></li>
              <li><p>The variable was removed from the model during bootstrapping.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>A. If the 95% CI for a partial slope includes 0, we cannot rule out the possibility that <m>\beta_j = 0</m>, meaning the variable may not have a statistically significant relationship with the response.</p></answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="lc10-26">
          <statement>
            <p>
              In hypothesis testing for the partial slopes using permutation tests, what does
              it mean if an observed test statistic falls far to the right of the null
              distribution?
            </p>
            <ol label="A">
              <li><p>The variable is likely to have no effect on the response.</p></li>
              <li><p>The null hypothesis should be accepted.</p></li>
              <li><p>The variable is likely statistically significant, and we should reject the null.</p></li>
              <li><p>The observed data should be discarded.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer><p>C. If the observed test statistic falls far outside the null distribution, there is strong evidence against the null hypothesis, suggesting the partial slope is significantly different from zero.</p></answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>

    </subsection><!-- end HT for partial slopes using infer -->

  </section><!-- end Simulation-based inference for MLR -->


  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section xml:id="inference-conclusion">
    <title>Conclusion</title>

    <subsection xml:id="inference-summary">
      <title>Summary of statistical inference</title>

      <p>
        Armed with the regression modeling techniques you learned in
        <xref ref="regression"/> and <xref ref="multiple-regression"/>, your understanding
        of sampling for inference in <xref ref="sampling"/>, and the tools for statistical
        inference like confidence intervals and hypothesis tests in
        <xref ref="confidence-intervals"/> and <xref ref="hypothesis-testing"/>, you're now
        equipped to study the significance of relationships between variables in a wide array
        of data! Many of the ideas presented here can be extended into multiple regression
        and other more advanced modeling techniques.
      </p>
      <p>
        Throughout this chapter, we have covered six scenarios for inference that build on
        one another:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for a single mean (using <m>t</m>-distribution and bootstrap).</p></li>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for a single proportion (using normal approximation and bootstrap).</p></li>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for the difference in two means (using <m>t</m>-distribution and permutation).</p></li>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for the difference in two proportions (using normal approximation and permutation).</p></li>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for a simple linear regression slope (using <m>t</m>-distribution and bootstrap/permutation).</p></li>
        <li><p>Confidence intervals and hypothesis tests for multiple linear regression partial slopes (using <m>t</m>-distribution and bootstrap/permutation).</p></li>
      </ol>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="inference-for-regression-additional-resources">
      <title>Additional resources</title>

      <p>
        An R script file of all R code used in this chapter is available
        <url href="https://moderndive.com/v2/scripts/10-inference-for-regression.R">here</url>.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="what-is-to-come-ch10">
      <title>What's to come</title>

      <p>
        You've now concluded the last major part of this book on statistical inference with
        <c>infer</c>. The closing <xref ref="thinking-with-data"/> concludes this book with
        various short case studies involving real data, such as house prices in the city of
        Seattle, Washington in the US. You'll see how the principles in this book can help
        you become a great storyteller with data!
      </p>
    </subsection>

  </section><!-- end Conclusion -->
</chapter>
